710741f-a.text:
Eleventh Avenue, east side, north from W. 58th (right) to 59th Streets, showing a fenced area where gas holders formerly stood. Beyond 59th Street this thoroughfare changes its name to become West End Avenue, therefore the Empire Storage Warehouse is at the N.W. corner of that and W. 59th Street.

September 19, 1933.
Views 1 and 2

P. L. Sperr

The New York Sun of September 29, 1938 reports the demolition of No. 2-10 West End Avenue and 557-63 West 59th Street, a five story warehouse formerly occupied by the National Gum and Mica Co. This appears in this view as the Empire Storage Warehouse Co.

713988f-a.text:
58th Street, east from Eleventh Avenue.
May 8, 1935.
P. L. Sperr.

710740f-a.text:
11th Avenue, east side, north from W. 58th Street. This thoroughfare loses its identity at 59th Street, to become known as West End Avenue. The cleared lot in the foreground occupies the entire 58th - 59th Street frontage. Note the vacant site at the N. E. corner of 59th Street where the old Empire Warehouse stood.
October 24, 1939
Views 1,2
P. L. Sperr

710739f-c.text:
11th Avenue, east side, north from W. 58th Street, showing the cleared 58th - 59th Street frontage and the beginning of West End Avenue. The latter, technically starts at 59th Street and therefore the buildings seen are on same. On the left are the extensive New
York Central Railroad yards.
Views 1,2: May 8, 1935
View 3: November 25, 1937
P. L. Sperr
